SIMPLE: protest
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Protest
<hw>Pro*test"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. &
p. p.</pos> <conjf>Protested</conjf>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Protesting</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[F. <ets>protester</ets>, L.
<ets>protestari</ets>, <ets>pro</ets> before + <ets>testari</ets> to be
a witness, <ets>testis</ets> a witness. See <er>Testify</er>.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>To affirm in a public or formal manner; to bear
witness; to declare solemnly; to avow.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He <qex>protest</qex> that his measures are pacific.</q>
<rj><qau>Landor.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The lady doth <qex>protest</qex> too much, methinks.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To make a solemn declaration (often a written one)
expressive of opposition; -- with <xex>against</xex>; <as>as, he
<ex>protest</ex> against your votes</as>.</def>
<rj><au>Denham.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The conscience has power . . . to <qex>protest</qex> againts the
exorbitancies of the passions.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- To affirm; asseverate; assert; aver; attest;
testify; declare; profess. See <er>Affirm</er>.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Protest</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Protest
<hw>Pro*test"</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To make a solemn
declaration or affirmation of; to proclaim; to display; <as>as, to
<ex>protest</ex> one's loyalty</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I will <qex>protest</qex> your cowardice.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To call as a witness in affirming or denying, or to
prove an affirmation; to appeal to.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Fiercely [they] opposed⟦br⟧
My journey strange, with clamorous uproar⟦br⟧
<qex>Protesting</qex> fate supreme.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><mcol><col><b>To protest a bill</b></col> <it>or</it> <col><b>To
protest a note</b></col></mcol> <fld>(Law)</fld>, <cd>to make a solemn
written declaration, in due form, on behalf of the holder, against all
parties liable for any loss or damage to be sustained by the
nonacceptance or the nonpayment of the bill or note, as the case may be.
This should be made by a notary public, whose seal it is the usual
practice to affix.</cd> <rj><au>Kent.</au> <au>Story.</au></rj></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Protest</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Protest
<hw>Pro"test</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F.
<ets>prot⟦ecir⟧t</ets>, It. <ets>protesto</ets>. See <er>Protest</er>,
<pos>v.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A solemn declaration of opinion,
commonly a formal objection against some act; especially, a formal and
solemn declaration, in writing, of dissent from the proceedings of a
legislative body; <as>as, the <ex>protest</ex> of lords in
Parliament</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Law)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>A solemn declaration
in writing, in due form, made by a notary public, usually under his
notarial seal, on behalf of the holder of a bill or note, protesting
against all parties liable for any loss or damage by the nonacceptance
or nonpayment of the bill, or by the nonpayment of the note, as the case
may be.</def> <sd>(b)</sd> <def>A declaration made by the master of a
vessel before a notary, consul, or other authorized officer, upon his
arrival in port after a disaster, stating the particulars of it, and
showing that any damage or loss sustained was not owing to the fault of
the vessel, her officers or crew, but to the perils of the sea, etc.,
ads the case may be, and protesting against them.</def> <sd>(c)</sd>
<def>A declaration made by a party, before or while paying a tax, duty,
or the like, demanded of him, which he deems illegal, denying the
justice of the demand, and asserting his rights and claims, in order to
show that the payment was not voluntary.</def> <au>Story.</au>
<au>Kent.</au>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Protestancy</ent>⟦br⟧
